ries to reason with Trevor when he insists he will tell Rose how he feels at her rehearsal dinner. In anger, Trevor posts in the podcast comments that Miles is hiding his feelings for Cara. Miles asks Rakesh to down the post as soon as he sees it. With help from Rakesh's soul mate app, Miles shows Trevor there is likely someone else who is right for him, but Trevor follows through on his plan. Though it leads to Rose telling Trevor she doesn't love him that way, Trevor gets needed closure, prompting him to tell Miles he should say how he feels about Cara. However, Adam saw the earlier post from Trevor, and he breaks up with Cara. Meanwhile, Rakesh, Zack and Corey are able to successfully hack the DoD, but while trying to locate the source of the code, the program crashes. Rakesh interprets this as the God account protecting itself, but later learns that Corey intends to destroy the account. Also, Ali becomes suspicious when Emily lies about seeing another woman.\n |LineColor       = 549FC3\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 41\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 21\n |Title           = Miracles\n |RTitle          = <ref name=\"TFC\" />\n |DirectedBy      =\n |WrittenBy       = \n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|26}}\n |ProdCode        = \n |Viewers         = \n |ShortSummary    = <!-- Episode summaries must be expressed in your own words. Do NOT submit content you find from another web site as it is plagiarism and likely a copyright violation, which Wikipedia cannot accept and will be removed or reverted. Superficially modifying copyrighted content or closely paraphrasing it, even if the source is cited, still constitutes a copyright violation. Summaries should be about 100 to 200 words in length, per MOS:TVPLOT, and those substantially less than 100 words are most likely to be scrutinized for possible copyright violation. -->\n |LineColor       = 549FC3\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 42\n |EpisodeNumber2  = 22\n |Title           = The Mountain\n |RTitle          = <ref name=\"TFC\" />\n |DirectedBy      =\n |WrittenBy       = \n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|4|26}}\n |ProdCode        = \n |Viewers         = \n |ShortSummary    = <!-- Episode summaries must be expressed in your own words. Do NOT submit content you find from another web site as it is plagiarism and likely a copyright violation, which Wikipedia cannot accept and will be removed or reverted. Superficially modifying copyrighted content or closely paraphrasing it, even if the source is cited, still constitutes a copyright violation. Summaries should be about 100 to 200 words in length, per MOS:TVPLOT, and those substantially less than 100 words are most likely to be scrutinized for possible copyright violation. -->\n |LineColor       = 549FC3\n}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nOn August 31, 2017, it was announced that both Steven Lilien and Wynbrandt had decided to develop the new pilot and had teamed with [[Greg Berlanti]] and [[Sarah Schechter]] to develop the concept. [[Warner Bros. Television]] was shopping the show to the American broadcast networks. Both Lilien and Wynbrandt would write the series, while both Berlanti and Schechter would serve as executive producer and [[Marcos Siega]] would direct the pilot.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2017/08/god-friended-me-light-drama-greg-berlanti-marcos-siega-cbs-steven-lilien-and-bryan-wynbrandt-1202151792/|title='God Friended Me' Light Procedural From \u2018Alcatraz\u2019 Co-Creators, Berlanti Prods. & Marcos Siega Lands At CBS As Put Pilot|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=August 31, 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|language=en-US|access-date=September 1, 2017}}</ref> CBS ordered a pilot on January 23, 2018. In addition to Berlanti, Schechter, Lilien, and Wynbrandt would serve as executive producers for the series.<ref name=\"order\"/> The pilot was picked up straight-to-series by [[CBS]] on May 11, 2018<ref name=\"order\"/> and the series premiered on September 30, 2018.<ref name=\"PremiereDates\"/> On October 19, 2018, CBS picked up the series for a full season of 20 episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/the-neighborhood-magnum-pi-god-friended-me-full-season-orders-cbs-1202485957/|title='The Neighborhood', 'Magnum P.I.' & 'God Friended Me' Get CBS Full-Season Orders|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=October 19, 2018|accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn January 29, 2019, the series was renewed for a second season<ref name=\"S2Renewal\"/> which premiered on September 29, 2019. On March 13, 2020, Warner Bros. Television announced that production would be suspended due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/batwoman-young-sheldon-the-bachelorette-shut-down-warner-bros-tv-group-suspends-production-series-pilots-coronavirus-1202882685/|title='Batwoman', 'Young Sheldon', 'The Bachelorette' & More Shut Down As Warner Bros. TV Group Suspends Production On Series & Pilots Over Coronavirus|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref> On April 14, 2020, CBS announced the series had been canceled after two seasons and would end the series on April 26, 2020.<ref name=\"Cancellation\"/>\n\n===Casting===\nOn February 5, 2018, it was announced that [[Brandon Micheal Hall]] had joined the production as Miles Finer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2018/02/brandon-micheal-hall-cast-the-lead-cbs-pilot-god-friended-me-berlanti-prods-the-mayor-canceled-1202278516/|title='The Mayor' Star Brandon Micheal Hall Cast As The Lead Of CBS Pilot 'God Friended Me' From Berlanti Prods.|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=February 5, 2018|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|language=en-US|access-date=February 5, 2018}}</ref> Several additional cast members were announced in February 2018. Javicia Leslie and [[Suraj Sharma]] are both portrayed as Rakesh Singh and Ali Finer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2018/02/god-friended-me-javicia-leslie-suraj-sharma-cast-cbs-drama-pilot-1202292412/|title='God Friended Me': Javicia Leslie & Suraj Sharma Cast In CBS Drama Pilot|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=February 16, 2018|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|language=en-US|access-date=February 17, 2018}}</ref>, then four days later [[Joe Morton]] is Rev. Arthur Finer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2018/02/god-friended-me-joe-morton-cast-lead-cbs-drama-pilot-scandal-1202296973/|title='God Friended Me': 'Scandal's Joe Morton To Co-Star In CBS Drama Pilot|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|last2=Petski|first2=Denise|date=February 20, 2018|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|language=en-US|access-date=February 22, 2018}}</ref> Finally, [[Violett Beane]] was cast as Cara Bloom.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2018/02/god-friended-me-violett-beane-star-cbs-drama-pilot-1202305944/|title='God Friended Me': Violett Beane To Star In CBS Comedic Drama Pilot About Faith|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|last2=Petski|first2=Denise|date=February 28, 2018|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|language=en-US|access-date=March 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn June 11, 2019, it was reported that [[Erica Gimpel]] was promoted as a series regular for second season.<ref >{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/god-friended-me-erica-gimpel-promotd-series-regular-season-2-cbs-drama-1202631109/|title='God Friended Me': Erica Gimpel Upped To Series Regular For Season 2 Of CBS Drama|last=Petski|first=Denise|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=June 11, 2019|accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical response===\nOn the [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the series has an approval rating of 61%  based on 28 reviews, with an average rating of 6.36 out of 10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"A sincere and thoughtful handling of spiritual themes helps ''God Friended Me'' overcome\u2014and even benefit from\u2014its earnest approach to a potentially off-putting premise.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/god_friended_me/s01/ |title=''God Friended Me'': Season 1 (2018)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=January 5, 2019}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], which uses a weighted average, assigned a score of 57 out of 100 based on 14 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/god-friended-me |title=''God Friended Me'' Season 1: (2018)|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=October 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn his review of the show's pilot episode, Matthew Gilbert of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' wrote that \"Based on the title alone, I was fully prepared to despise this show\", but declared that \"the premiere holds some promise as a thoughtful feel-good drama.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/2018/09/21/the-good-bad-and-maybes-fall-premieres/8Cdf93ieDoVNK1gSxkM5XL/story.html|title=TV\u2019s new shows this fall, from binge to cringe|last=Gilbert|first=Matthew|date=September 21, 2018|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|accessdate=July 24, 2019}}</ref> Michael Starr of the ''[[New York Post]]'' wrote that \"While 'God Friended Me' does sometimes stray into saccharine-sweet, '[[Touched By An Angel]]'-type territory [...] it doesn't overstay its welcome and seems to know when to dial it back and inject some levity into the proceedings.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2018/12/14/god-friended-me-fall-finale-hits-close-to-home-for-miles/|title=\u2018God Friended Me\u2019 fall finale hits close to home for Miles|last=Starr|first=Michael|date=December 14, 2018|work=[[The New York Post]]|accessdate=July 24, 2019}}</ref> Steve Greene of [[IndieWire]] gave the show a grade of \"C\", writing that \"It's anchored by a likable cast, and works from an admirably high-concept premise, but for now the result is an overstuffed hodgepodge of exaggerated emotions and familiar swings at family drama.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/09/god-friended-me-review-cbs-show-1202007018/|title=\u2018God Friended Me\u2019 Review: This Sentimental CBS Drama Has Trouble Keeping Up With God as Its Star|last=Greene|first=Steve|date=September 30, 2018|website=[[IndieWire]]|accessdate=July 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nVinnie Mancuso of [[Collider (website)|Collider]] gave the show a rating of three stars, calling Hall's performance as Miles \"endlessly likable\" but writing that the show is \"heavy on the hamminess, rooted in religion and old-fashioned morality, and misunderstands the lifestyle of your average human under the age of 35 on every fundamental level\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/god-friended-me-review/|title=\u2018God Friended Me\u2019 Review: God Bless This Mess|last=Mancuso|first=Vinnie|date=September 28, 2018|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|accessdate=July 24, 2019}}</ref> [[Hemant Mehta]] of [[Patheos]] wrote that ''God Friended Me'' is \"not a bad show\", but criticized the show for presenting Miles' atheism as being a result of his mother's death.<ref name=mehta>{{cite web|url=https://friendlyatheist.patheos.com/2018/09/10/heres-the-biggest-problem-with-the-atheist-character-in-cbs-god-friended-me/|title=Here\u2019s the Biggest Problem with the Atheist Character in CBS\u2019 God Friended Me|last=Mehta|first=Hemant|authorlink=Hemant Mehta|date=September 10, 2018|website=[[Patheos]]|accessdate=July 24, 2019}}</ref> Mehta wrote that \"In short, he's an atheist because he went through something traumatic [...] it bears no resemblance to why so many atheists today don't believe in God.\"<ref name=mehta />\n\n===Ratings===\nThe website ''TV Series Finale'' acknowledged that during the show's second season, ratings averaged 25% less in the key 18-49 demo compared to the first season.<ref name=\"Cancellationandfinale\">{{cite news|url=https://tvseriesfinale.com/tv-show/god-friended-me-cancelled-by-cbs-no-season-three/|title=God Friended Me: Cancelled by CBS; No Season Three|first=Jessica|last=Pena|publisher=TV Series Finale|date=April 14, 2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref> Overall viewership also fell 20% compared to the first season as well.<ref name=\"Cancellationandfinale\"/> [[TV Line]] also reported that God Friended Me had the \"smallest gain via Live+7 DVR playback \u2014 just 23 percent \u2014 of any scripted CBS program.\"<ref name=\"Cancellation\"/>\n\n====Season 1====\n{{Television episode ratings\n| width     = 99\n\n| title1    = [[#ep1|Pilot]]\n| date1     = September 30, 2018\n| rs1       = 1.3/5\n| viewers1  = 10.14<ref name=\"1.01\"/>\n| dvr1      = n/a\n| dvrv1     = 2.01\n| total1    = n/a\n| totalv1   = 12.15<ref>{{cite web|url=https://programminginsider.com/live7-weekly-ratings-manifest-is-most-watched-nbc-drama-series-premiere-in-19-years/|title=Live+7 Weekly Ratings: ''Manifest'' is Most-Watched NBC Drama Series Premiere in 19 Years|last=Pucci|first=Douglas|date=October 10, 2018|work=Programming Insider|accessdate=October 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n| title2    = [[#ep2|The Good Samaritan]]\n| date2     = October 7, 2018\n| rs2       = 0.9/4\n| viewers2  = 8.37<ref name=\"1.02\"/>\n| dvr2      = n/a\n| dvrv2     = 1.91\n| total2    = n/a\n| totalv2   = 10.29<ref>{{cite web|url=https://programminginsider.com/live7-weekly-ratings-long-running-stalwarts-the-big-bang-theory-and-modern-family-lead-all-network-comedies-in-adults-18-49-gains/|title=Live+7 Weekly Ratings: Long-running Stalwarts ''The Big Bang Theory'' and ''Modern Family'' Lead All Network Comedies in Adults 18-49 Gains|last=Pucci|first=Douglas|date=October 16, 2018|work=Programming Insider|accessdate=October 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n| title3    = [[#ep3|Heavenly Taco Truck]]\n| date3     = October 14, 2018\n| rs3       = 1.0/5\n| viewers3  = 7.90<ref name=\"1.03\"/>\n| dvr3      = 0.4\n| dvrv3     = 2.11\n| total3    = 1.4\n| totalv3   = 10.01<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/live-plus-7-ratings-oct-8-manifest-1202990062/|title=Live+7 Ratings for Week of Oct. 8: ''Manifest'' Doubles In Week 3|last=